===Pronunciation===
*nā'shən, /ˈneɪʃən/, /<tt>"neIS@n</tt>/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-eɪʃən|Rhymes: -eɪʃən]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# A group of people sharing aspects of language, culture and/or ethnicity.
#: ''The Roma are a '''nation''' without a country.''
# {{law}} (''international law'') A sovereign state.
#: ''Though legally single '''nations''', many states comprise several distinct cultural or ethnic groups.''

===Usage Note===
{{UK}} Following the establishment of the Scottish and Welsh [[parliament|parliaments]], [[England]], [[Scotland]] and [[Wales]] are normally considered distinct nations. Application of the term ''nation'' to the United Kingdom as a whole is [[deprecate|deprecated]] in most style guides, including the BBC, most newspapers and in UK Government publications. [[Northern Ireland]], being of less clear legal status, generally remains a [[province]].

